s with parents and teens, Not Under My Roof offers an unprecedented, intimate account of the different ways that girls and boys in both countries negotiate love, lust, and growing up. Tracing the roots of the parents’ divergent attitudes, Amy T. Schalet reveals how they grow out of their respective conceptions of the self, relationships, gender, autonomy, and authority. She provides a probing analysis of the way family culture shapes not just sex but also alcohol consumption and parent-teen relationships. Avoiding caricatures of permissive Europeans and puritanical Americans, Schalet shows that the Dutch require self-control from teens and parents, while Americans guide their children toward autonomous adulthood at the expense of the family bond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aParent and teenagerxNetherlands. 0aParent and teenagerxUnited States. 0aParent and teenagerzNetherlands. 0aParent and teenagerzUnited States. 0aTeenagersxSexual behaviorxNetherlands. 0aTeenagersxSexual behaviorxUnited States. 0aTeenagersxSexual behaviorzNetherlands. 0aTeenagersxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aparents, parenting, families, familial relationships, teens, teenagers, children, child, parent-child, sex, sociology, sociologist, sexuality education, youth, united states of america, american culture, usa, cultural studies, netherlands, interviews, girls, boys, men, women, love, lust, attraction, growing up, gender, autonomy, alcohol, parent-teen, romance, romantic, adolescence, individualism, control, connection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226736204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226736204/original  a978-